Preheat your oven to 200 degrees. Chop the @sweet potato{1%small} into 2cm chunks
(no need to peel!) and then pick the @thyme{1}(leaves picked from stalks) leaves
from their stalks.

Pop your sweet potato on a lined #baking tray{}, sprinkle over half your thyme
leaves and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Add a glug of @oil{glug}, toss
well and then roast in your oven for ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Tip: Make sure they are all in one layer and turn halfway through in order to
> cook evenly.

Cut the @echalion shallot{1} in half through the root. Peel and chop half your
shallot into small chunks. Keep the other half whole and push the pointy end of
the @cloves{2} into it (this will make it easier to remove them from your bread
sauce later).

Cut the top and bottom off the @courgette{1} and slice into rounds 1cm thick.
Keep to one side.

Start making the bread sauce by infusing the milk with your cloved studded
shallot. Heat a #small saucepan{} over medium heat and add a little @oil{}. Add
your chopped shallot and leftover thyme leaves and cook for ~{5%minutes}. Pour
in the @milk{189%ml} and add your clove studded shallot. Warm your milk until
it is steaming then remove from the heat. We will finish your bread sauce later.

Season each @duck breasts{2} with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Put them skin-side
down in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. As the heat of the pan melts the duck
fat under the skin, drain the fat into a #bowl{}. Continue for ~{5-7%minutes}
until the skin is golden brown and crispy.

> Tip: Keep the drained duck fat in your fridge and use it to roast potatoes,
> delicious!

Turn your duck over, brown the flesh side and then transfer to the baking tray
with your sweet potato. Roast for ~{7-9%minutes} if you like your duck pink or
~{12-15%minutes} if you like it well done.

Wipe your frying pan clean with kitchen paper and return to high heat. Cook
your courgette for ~{3-4%minutes} until nicely browned. Remove the pan from the
heat, allow to cool for a few mins, then drizzle in the @honey{1%tbsp}. Coat
your courgette in your honey.

When your duck is ready, allow it to rest on a #chopping board{} whilst you
finish your bread sauce. Remove your clove studded shallot from your milk and
bring your milk to the boil on medium heat. Mix in the @panko breadcrumbs{20%g}
and cook until they have softened and you have a sauce the consistency of
porridge. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and get ready to plate up!

Slice each duck breast into five or six slices. Smear a spoonful of bread sauce
in the centre of your plate. Pop a layer of courgette on top followed by your
roast duck. Arrange your sweet potatoes alongside and drizzle any honey from
the pan over and around. Serve your remaining bread sauce on the side. Enjoy!